  "text": "The Rust compiler and Servo browser engine share code through the proc_macro bridge, a standardized RPC interface defined in the Rust standard library. This connection allows Servo's procedural macros (such as dom_struct and servo_tracing) to communicate with the Rust compiler during compilation.\n\n**Servo Repository (servo/servo):**\nServo's style and selectors crates are not stored locally in the current snapshot but are external dependencies from https://github.com/servo/stylo (git revision 3b46f3ef27eb14ca276b4bf3ff041a6c43d93827). The root Cargo.toml (lines 160, 178-182) declares dependencies on:\n- selectors: the CSS selector parsing and matching crate\n- stylo: the style system crate (imported as 'style' in code)\n- servo_arc: atomic reference counting utilities\n- stylo_atoms, stylo_config, stylo_dom, stylo_traits: related style system components\n\nServo components use the style crate throughout the codebase. For example, components/layout/style_ext.rs imports from style's computed_values, properties, and logical_geometry modules. Tests in tests/unit/style/ directly test the style system through its public API.\n\nServo's procedural macros (dom_struct in components/dom_struct/lib.rs and servo_tracing in components/servo_tracing/lib.rs) depend on the proc_macro crate from the Rust standard library, establishing the connection to the compiler.\n\n**Rust Compiler (rust-lang/rust):**\nThe proc_macro bridge is defined in library/proc_macro/src/bridge/ and provides the RPC interface for procedural macros:\n\n- bridge/mod.rs: Defines the higher-order macro with_api! that generates type-safe RPC APIs for both client and server sides. This file defines the core types used in macro expansion: TokenStream, Span, Symbol, Literal, Ident, Group, Punct, and DelimSpan.\n- bridge/client.rs: Client-side implementation with the Client struct and handle management. Exposes is_available() function to detect if code is running inside a procedural macro context.\n- bridge/server.rs: Server-side implementation with the run_server function that orchestrates macro execution. The Server trait defines the interface for compiler-provided functionality.\n\nThe bridge uses a serialization protocol with C ABI buffers and unique integer handles to safely interface between proc macro crates and the compiler, accommodating potentially mismatching Rust ABIs during bootstrap (e.g., stage0 vs stage1 rustc).\n\n**Code Sharing Mechanism:**\nThe connection flows through Servo's build process: when Servo's proc_macro attributes (like #[dom_struct]) are invoked during compilation, they communicate with the Rust compiler through the proc_macro bridge defined in library/proc_macro. This allows Servo to use procedural macros for code generation while maintaining compatibility with the compiler's macro expansion infrastructure."
}

